Hitman freelancer sentiment analysis¶

Abstract¶

The main goal is to apply sentiment analysis on comments within the Hitman Forum surrounding Hitman freelancer feeedback, official site for Hitman geeks like me.

Goals¶

  1. Parse text from thread Official: H3 Freelancer Closed Technical Test feedback Thread (CTT) . Hopefuly in the future this can be expanded upon from you developers of this amazing mode.
  2. Apply EDA on the data
  3. Clean the data for some good old fashioned Statistical based Natural Language Processing
  4. Apply the EDA and retrieve some useful feedback for developers.
  5. Get an offline mode for World of Assassination

# Basic preprocessing: remove, punctation, lowercase, replace plural forms with singular
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: re.sub('[,.!?:)../.)(]','',x))
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: x.lower())
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: x.replace("'",""))
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: x.replace("missions","mission"))
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: x.replace("weaopons","weapon"))
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: x.replace("rewards","reward"))
data['Abstract'] = data['Abstract'].map(lambda x: x.replace("targets","target"))

As we can see above from word frequency, function words are dominant (eg 'the','a' and so on), also called stop words these will be also removed during data processing. We can also notice that some words have frequency 1. These are called Hapax legomenon from Greek "read only once" and have little use for us. These will be later droped as there give us no meaningful insight. For further reading see Zip's law.

data['Abstract'] = [' '.join([j for j in i if c[j] > k]) for i in v]

As we can see: missions, targets, objectives and time was used a lot in our feedback. To see their sentient, we firstly need to classify each corpus as positive,negative or neutral (most likely bugs, or just base comments). For this purpose we will use twitter-xlm-roberta-base-sentiment, already pretrained model on a huge dataset. So it really doesn't matter that our is so small. Threshold for positive/negative classification will be 0.6 >=, otherwise classify as neutral.

from transformers import TFAutoModelForSequenceClassification
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoConfig
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
from scipy.special import softmax
In [19]:
class LabelSentiment:
    def __init__(self, threshold: float, data):
        self.MODEL = "cardiffnlp/twitter-xlm-roberta-base-sentiment"

        self.tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(self.MODEL)
        self.config = AutoConfig.from_pretrained(self.MODEL)

        # TF : TensorFlow
        self.model = TFAutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(self.MODEL)
        
        self.threshold = threshold
        self.data = data
        
    def get_score(self, abstract):
        encoded_input = self.tokenizer(abstract, return_tensors='tf')
        output = self.model(**encoded_input)
        score = tf.stop_gradient(output[0][0]).numpy()
        score = softmax(score)
        return score
    
    def get_label(self, abstract):
        max_score = None
        label = None
        score = self.get_score(abstract)
        ranking = np.argsort(score)
        ranking = ranking[::-1]
        for i in range(score.shape[0]):
            s = score[ranking[i]]
            s = s.item()
            label = self.config.id2label[ranking[i]]
            if max_score is None or max_score < s:
                max_score = s
                best_label = label
        if max_score < self.threshold:
            best_label = 'Neutral'

        return best_label
    
    def assign_label(self):
        labels = []
        for index, row in self.data.iterrows():
            labels.append(self.get_label(str(row)))
        return labels

           
label = LabelSentiment(0.5, data)
labels_ls = label.assign_label()

All model checkpoint layers were used when initializing TFXLMRobertaForSequenceClassification.

All the layers of TFXLMRobertaForSequenceClassification were initialized from the model checkpoint at cardiffnlp/twitter-xlm-roberta-base-sentiment.
If your task is similar to the task the model of the checkpoint was trained on, you can already use TFXLMRobertaForSequenceClassification for predictions without further training.

import gensim

def sentences_to_words(sentences):
    for sentence in sentences:
        yield(gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(str(sentence), deacc=True))
